Registers:
Note: There are acctually two different syntaxes ( syntax style or call "Flavor") for assembly, intel and AT&T, i will focus on Intel for now. But keep note that AT&T is more commonly used for Linux (?)
Both Intel and AT&T syntaxes are used to write instructions for the same underlying processor (like an x86 or x86-64 chip). 


In a process of a c program, you may know that the compiler must convert it to assembly language so computer can understand.

In windows, assembly file code can be:
- Source code : Contain human readable assembly instruction
Can be .asm, .s, .S, .inc

- Compiled & Intermediate ext: when source code is processed by an assembler, it is saved into binary file to keep the instruction
Can be .exe, .obj, .dll and .lst

Special case .NET assemblies (?)

Small example:
---
nasm
; hello.asm - 64-bit Windows Hello World (NASM)
extern MessageBoxA
extern ExitProcess

section .data
    caption db 'Assembly Example', 0
    message db 'Hello, this is a small source code!', 0

section .text
    global main
main:
    ; Register-based calling convention for x64 Windows (Shadow Space)
    sub rsp, 28h          ; Reserve 40 bytes of shadow space on stack
    
    mov rcx, 0            ; HWND hWnd = NULL
    mov rdx, message      ; LPCSTR lpText
    mov r8, caption       ; LPCSTR lpCaption
    mov r9, 0             ; UINT uType = MB_OK
    call MessageBoxA      ; Call the Windows API
    
    mov rcx, 0            ; UINT uExitCode = 0
    call ExitProcess      ; Exit the program
---
To turn this into a program we need an assembler and a linker
First assembler
nasm -f win64 hello.asm -o hello.obj
Second link
link hello.obj /subsystem:windows /entry:main user32.lib kernel32.lib /out:hello.exe

